They should come with a rope, but if they don't, you should buy some. There are strap kits available for trees so that you don't damage them by drilling in screws or having ropes strip the bark. Figure out how high or low you want to be while laying in it. Then, because the hammock will stretch, put it up about two feet higher than you want. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Wrap the rope around the tree or attach it to the pole. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/53/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/53/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Bring the rope around the tree/pole to where the end is facing you. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Tie it in a sailor's knot, then come around the tree/pole again, and repeat the sailor's knot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3b/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3b/Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Camp-Comfortably-With-a-Hammock-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
